cs.LG, cs.NE, cs.CV, cs.SI, cs.CE 

The paper proposes a method based on deep neural networks for multi-way data analysis in the context of smart infrastructure damage detection and diagnosis. The method uses a multi-objective variational autoencoder to extract informative features from multi-sensor data and generate probabilistic anomaly scores for damage detection and severity assessment. The paper also introduces a new localization layer in the autoencoder for damage localization. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), and cs.CV (Computer Vision), as the paper heavily relies on deep neural networks and probabilistic modeling. The sub-categories cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) are also possible, as the paper deals with data analysis in the context of smart infrastructure maintenance.
